# Figma — NAMING_CONVENTION (design system, agent-friendly)

Consult this when **creating, renaming, or auditing** Figma artifacts: **pages**, **frames/layers**, **variables/collections**, **text/effect styles**, **components**, and **component properties**. Goal: **one predictable vocabulary** for humans, devs, and **LLM/agents** (MCP, plugins, codegen) — close the **semantic gap** (appearance vs meaning).

**Reference (philosophy):** [Your design system wasn’t built for AI](https://medium.com/design-bootcamp/your-design-system-wasnt-built-for-ai-here-s-what-to-do-about-it-69e9cba80f1f) — object-oriented cues in file structure and names; encode **objects**, **attributes**, **states**, and **capabilities**, not only pixels.

**Fichier DS Stoodio (variables & styles)** — [DS Styles sur Figma](https://www.figma.com/design/3asFmiQJbu3XBt9ubUcjiA/-DS----Styles) (`fileKey` **3asFmiQJbu3XBt9ubUcjiA** ; nom de fichier **\[DS\] - Styles**). Les règles **`Display mode`** ci‑dessous sont alignées sur **`ds-tokens-builder`** : pas de dossier **`Semantics`** ; les rôles chromatiques / par composant vivent sous **`{Category}/Components/{Component}/…`** quand le composant publié le requiert.

---

## Principles for agent-native names (LLM-friendly)

1. **Name the object, not only the shell** — Prefer `SubscriptionCard`, `InvoiceRow`, `UserSummary` over generic `Card`, `Row`, `Block` when the instance is tied to a **domain entity**. Agents map names to product models; generics force guesswork.
2. **Stable vocabulary** — One term per concept across variables, components, and layers (no mix of `primary` / `main` / `brand` for the same role). Agents search and compose by string match.
3. **Explicit state and mode** — Model non–happy-path states (`Loading`, `Error`, `Empty`, `Disabled`) in **variants** or variables, not only in designers’ heads. Variant axes should read like enums: `State`, `Status`, `Mode`, `View`.
4. **Variables = attributes; props = capabilities (when relevant)** — Collections/paths can reflect attributes (`…/status`, role, amount). Component properties that express **permissions or behavior** should read clearly to code: see **Booleans** below.
5. **Predictable paths** — Use consistent collection and slash structure (`Domain/Attribute` or existing token taxonomy). Avoid cryptic abbreviations and one-off spellings agents cannot infer.
6. **Describe intent in the label** — If two layers could look identical, the name must carry **role** or **binding** (what it is for), not `Group 47`.

---

## Casing (global)

- **Property names** (variant axes, text, boolean, instance-swap labels): **Title Case** — e.g. `Size`, `Shape`, `Icon L`, `Action R`, `Main navigation`.
- **Variant / dropdown values**: **Title Case** — e.g. `Large`, `Medium`, `X-Small`, `Past Due`, `Read Only`, `List Item`, `Idle`, `Full`.
- **Pages / major sections** — Follow **ds-page-builder** manifest conventions; use readable **Title Case** for section titles. **ALL CAPS** only for intentional coarse regions (`HEADER`, `FOOTER`) when aligned with existing patterns.
- **Layers inside published components** — Prefer **Title Case** or short **semantic** names; avoid `Frame 234` / `Rectangle 12` in shipped library internals when agents must diff structure.
- **Icon / small leaf components** (swap targets): keep library names **short**; often **lowercase** (`plus`, `globe`) — **asset name**, not the property label.

---

## Components and variants

- **Component name** — `[Domain][Role]` or `[Domain] [Role]` when domain-specific; keep **primitive** names (`Button`, `Input`) for truly generic UI atoms.
- **Variant axes** — **Short nouns**, **one concern per axis**: `Size`, `Shape`, `Type`, `State`, `Status`, `Device`, `Mode`, `View`. Prefer **`Status`** values that match **real domain states** (`Trialing`, `Active`, `Past Due`, `Canceled`) where applicable, not only visual adjectives.
- **Primary axes** — Besides `Size`/`Shape`, include axes that mirror **behavior** (`Mode = Read Only | Editable`, `View = List Item | Detail | Summary`) when the product has those modes.

---

## Booleans

Two families; pick by **what the flag means** (agents use this to infer UI rules).

### A — Visibility / chrome (presentation)

- Name the **thing toggled** (presence), not `Show …` / `Has …` / `is…` for **pure layout chrome**.
- **Disable** for disabled interaction — not `Disabled` / `isDisabled`.
- Examples: `Tabs`, `Footer`, `Dropdown`, `Icon`, `Label`, `Placeholder`, `Chips`, `Helper`, `Previous`, `Next`, `Alert`, `Toast`, `Modal`, `Connected`, `Menu Avatar`, `Lighting`, `Agent Fin`.

### B — Domain capabilities and data (product logic)

- When the flag mirrors **permissions, entitlements, or data** (article: “capabilities”), use **explicit, code-alignable** wording in **Title Case** so agents and devs share one reading:
  - **Can [action]** — e.g. `Can Cancel`, `Can Upgrade`
  - **Has [condition]** — e.g. `Has Outstanding Balance`
  - **Optional:** **Show [domain slice]** only when it encodes a **named product surface** (e.g. usage metrics), not arbitrary “show section 3”.
- Prefer aligning **spelling** with variables/APIs (`Past Due` vs `pastDue`) per team convention; document the mapping once.

